						<summary>

						<p>On the first pillar, second row (east) <hi rend="italic">maṇḍapa,</hi> in front of Śāntanāyaki shrine, Mihiruṇēśvara temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Year 7: 978 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>Slightly damaged. Records that an individual Aṇḍurai Aruḷvāḻkkai cleared the forest, reclaimed twelve <hi rend="italic">mā</hi> of land and endowed the same for burning two perpetual lamps to the god Mahādēva of Tirumiyachchūr, a <hi rend="italic">dēvadāna</hi> of Ambar-nāḍu for the merit of his parents. It is also mentioned that the land is situated to the north-east of the temple. The priests in charge of the sanctum agreed to maintain the temple.</p>						

						</summary>
